# azure-verfied-modules-settings-new-resource

Focused guide to add a **new instance** of an existing AVM-inspired resource/module configuration in `settings/<env>/`.

## Multi-Layer Architecture Overview

```
Azure Resource Configuration Layers (settings/<env>/)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

Layer 1: GLOBAL
└─── global/ (project-wide settings, feature toggles, backend)

Layer 2: CORE (Shared Foundations)
├─── core/resource-groups.tf
├─── core/user-managed-identities.tf
├─── core/kv.tf
├─── core/la.tf
├─── core/app-ins.tf
├─── core/ad-groups.tf
└─── core/ (networking: VNets, subnets, DNS)

Layer 3: SERVICE DEPENDENCIES (Check ALL that apply)
├─── storage/ (storage accounts, containers, file shares)
├─── acr/ (container registries)
├─── adf/ (data pipelines)
├─── ai-search/ (search services)
├─── batch-account/ (batch compute)
├─── ml-studio/ (ML workspaces)
├─── ms-foundry/ (AI services)
└─── other services...

Layer 4: TARGET SERVICE
└─── <target-service>/ (final resource configuration)

CRITICAL RULE: Check layers 1→2→3→4 in order, ALWAYS.
Cross-environment: Repeat for reference env (dev/snd/test/prod).
```

## Inputs to Collect
- Environment(s): dev/snd/test/prod
- Resource type & service folder (e.g., storage, acr, ai-search)
- Add groups: new or reuse existing (check `core/ad-groups.tf`)
- Resource group: new or reuse existing (check `core/resource-groups.tf`)
- Identity: user-assigned or system MI (check `core/user-managed-identities.tf`)
- Key Vault usage: secrets/keys/certs (check `core/kv.tf`)
- Diagnostics: Log Analytics/App Insights (check `core/la.tf`, `core/app-ins.tf`)
- Networking: VNet/subnet, private endpoints, DNS zones; required subresources
- Tags: environment, project, owner, cost-center, managed-by

## Repository Layout (env-scoped)
- `settings/<env>/core/`
  - `ad-groups.tf` — AAD group mappings if RBAC/ownership needed
  - `resource-groups.tf` — define/reuse RGs
  - `user-managed-identities.tf` — define/reuse UAIs for workloads
  - `kv.tf` — secrets and access rules; add new secrets if needed
  - `app-ins.tf` / `la.tf` — monitoring resources and links
  - `main.tf` — shared locals, common data
- `settings/<env>/<service>/` — service-specific resource definitions + imports
- `settings/<env>/global/` — project/global locals, backend, feature toggless

## Workflow
1) **Study patterns**: Review `.github/skills/azure-verified-modules` (SKILL + references) for security defaults, validation, naming, outputs.

2) **Multi-layer context gathering** (CRITICAL - always perform ALL steps):
   - **Step 2a - Core layer**: Inspect `settings/<env>/core/*.tf` for shared foundations:
     - `resource-groups.tf` — available RGs to reuse
     - `user-managed-identities.tf` — available UAIs
     - `kv.tf` — Key Vault entries and access patterns
     - `la.tf` + `app-ins.tf` — diagnostics targets
     - `ad-groups.tf` — RBAC group patterns
   - **Step 2b - Global layer**: Check `settings/<env>/global/*.tf` for:
     - Project-wide locals and feature toggles
     - Backend configuration patterns
     - Environment-specific overrides
   - **Step 2c - Dependency layers**: For EVERY resource type, check ALL related service folders:
     - **Storage** (`settings/<env>/storage/`) — storage accounts, containers, file shares used by the resource
     - **ACR** (`settings/<env>/acr/`) — container registry access if deploying containerized workloads
     - **Networking** (may be in `core/` or separate) — VNets, subnets, private endpoints, DNS zones
     - **ADF** (`settings/<env>/adf/`) — data integration patterns if data pipelines involved
     - **AI Search** (`settings/<env>/ai-search/`) — search service dependencies
     - **Batch** (`settings/<env>/batch-account/`) — batch job patterns if compute workloads
     - **ML Studio** (`settings/<env>/ml-studio/`) — ML workspace integration
     - **MS Foundry** (`settings/<env>/ms-foundry/`) — AI services integration
   - **Step 2d - Target service layer**: Finally inspect the target service folder itself
   - **WHY**: Resources span layers. A web app may need: RG (core), MI (core), KV secrets (core), storage account (storage/), ACR image (acr/), App Insights (core), subnets (core/networking). Missing ANY layer check = incomplete config.

3) **Cross-environment mirror check** (for consistency):
   - Before adding to target env, check the SAME resource type in another env (e.g., dev → snd)
   - Scan ALL the same layers (core, global, storage, acr, target service) in the reference env
   - Note patterns: naming, tags, SKU progression, networking, diagnostics wiring
   - Identify intentional differences vs copy-forward patterns

4) **Plan placements**:
   - Shared foundations go to `core/` (RGs, UAIs, KV entries, diagnostics, ad groups) only if missing.
   - Service-specific config goes under the service folder (e.g., `storage/storage.tf`, `acr/acr.tf`).
   - Avoid duplicating existing RG/KV/MI; extend maps/objects instead.

5) **Private endpoints & IPs**:
   - Check current PEs/IPs in the target env subnet (scan existing files or query Azure via MCP). Select next free IP; double-check uniqueness.

6) **Implement with AVM-aligned defaults** (examples):
   - Enforce `public_network_access_enabled = false` where applicable.
   - `min_tls_version = "TLS1_2"`; `https_traffic_only_enabled = true` (storage/app services)
   - Managed identity preferred; no hardcoded secrets; use Key Vault data sources.
   - Diagnostics to Log Analytics; enable metrics/log categories per service.

7) **Variables/outputs**: Add inputs/outputs as needed; keep descriptions and validation; ensure required tags.

8) **Validate**: Run `terraform fmt -recursive` and `terraform validate` in the env folder; produce plan if required.

## Good Practices (quick list)
- Naming: `{type}-{workload}-{env}-{region}-{instance}`.
- Tags: environment, project, owner, cost-center, managed-by.
- Use existing RG/MI/KV where possible; avoid sprawl.
- Prefer private endpoints; restrict public network access.
- Use `for_each` for maps of instances in service files.
- Keep plan artifacts per env (dev/snd/test/prod) out of edits unless regenerating.

## Multi-Layer Verification Checklist

**Before making ANY changes, verify you have checked ALL applicable layers:**

### Core Layer (ALWAYS check)
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/resource-groups.tf` — RG existence and naming
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/user-managed-identities.tf` — MI availability and roles
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/kv.tf` — Key Vault entries and access policies
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/la.tf` — Log Analytics workspace
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/app-ins.tf` — Application Insights
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/ad-groups.tf` — AD groups for RBAC
- [ ] `settings/<env>/core/` (networking files) — VNets, subnets, DNS zones

### Global Layer (ALWAYS check)
- [ ] `settings/<env>/global/` — project locals, backend, feature toggles

### Service Dependency Layers (check based on resource type)
- [ ] `settings/<env>/storage/` — if resource needs storage accounts, containers, file shares
- [ ] `settings/<env>/acr/` — if resource needs container images
- [ ] `settings/<env>/adf/` — if resource involves data pipelines
- [ ] `settings/<env>/ai-search/` — if resource uses search indexing
- [ ] `settings/<env>/batch-account/` — if resource uses batch compute
- [ ] `settings/<env>/ml-studio/` — if resource integrates with ML workspace
- [ ] `settings/<env>/ms-foundry/` — if resource uses AI services
- [ ] `settings/<env>/linux-web-app/` — if related to web app deployments
- [ ] Other service folders as applicable

### Target Service Layer (ALWAYS check last)
- [ ] `settings/<env>/<target-service>/` — existing instances and patterns

### Cross-Environment Mirror (ALWAYS check)
- [ ] Repeat ALL above checks in reference environment (dev/snd/test/prod)
- [ ] Document differences between environments (intentional vs. oversight)

**FAIL FAST**: If you skip ANY applicable layer, the configuration will be incomplete. Always err on the side of checking too many layers.

